    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="541"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d541">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/4020: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">Then in France, to the <gloss type="to">Acting
                            Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">St. Jean de Luz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-08T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 8, 1936—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 8—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>178. John Whittaker, <hi rend="italic">Herald Tribune</hi> war correspondent, and
                    Miss Davis of <hi rend="italic">Chicago News</hi> both with rebel forces since
                    beginning, drove here from Burgos yesterday and called on me last night. They
                    report that Vitoria is threatened seriously by strong well-equipped Government
                    forces from Bilbao now within striking distance of city and that Franco,
                    alarmed, has weakened his army before Madrid by sending Moorish reinforcements.
                    The Loyalists clearly have retaken the towns between Bilbao and the present
                    position.</p>
                <p>They report that Salamanca resembles a German military camp, German officers
                    predominating. From a German officer on Madrid <pb facs="0693" n="594"
                        xml:id="pg_594"/> front Whittaker heard not for publication there is much
                    irritation among German and Italian officers because Franco objects to the
                    destruction of Madrid from the air.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
